T, and stick to your schedule. Even short daily practice sessions can add up to huge improvements.\n\n<h3>3. Focus on Understanding, Not Just Memorizing<\/h3>\n\nInstead of memorizing formulas or steps, aim to understand the underlying concepts. Khan Academy’s videos and explanations are designed to build conceptual knowledge, which helps you tackle novel problems more confidently.\n\n<h3>4. Use the Official SAT Practice Tests<\/h3>\n\nKhan Academy offers official SAT practice tests that mimic the real exam’s timing and difficulty. Use these tests periodically to gauge your progress and adjust your study plan as needed.\n\n<h3>5. Don’t Skip the Calculator and No-Calculator Sections<\/h3>\n\nThe SAT math section includes both calculator-permitted and no-calculator parts. Practice both types of questions on Khan Academy to ensure you’re comfortable with the pacing and strategies required for each.\n\n<h2>Integrating Khan Academy with Other Study Resources<\/h2>\n\nWhile Khan Academy is a powerful tool for SAT math prep, combining it with other study methods can provide a more well-rounded preparation experience.\n\n<h3>Supplementing with SAT Prep Books<\/h3>\n\nBooks like the Official SAT Study Guide or ones from reputable publishers can offer additional practice problems and detailed explanations. Use these alongside Khan Academy’s online resources to diversify your practice.\n\n<h3>Forming Study Groups<\/h3>\n\nSometimes, discussing math problems with peers can deepen understanding. Consider joining a study group where you can share Khan Academy lessons and collaborate on difficult questions.\n\n<h3>Getting Feedback from Teachers or Tutors<\/h3>\n\nIf possible, seek guidance from math teachers or tutors who can review your Khan Academy progress and help clarify challenging topics. Their insights can complement your self-study and keep you on track.\n\n<h2>Understanding the Scope of SAT Math on Khan Academy<\/h2>\n\nTo effectively utilize Khan Academy’s SAT math prep